%I A046873 #63 Jun 11 2026 17:17:43
%S A046873 1,1,2,48,1680384,14807804035657359360,
%T A046873 141377911697227887117195970316200795630205476957716480
%N A046873 Number of total orders extending inclusion on P({1,...,n}).
%C A046873 Trivial upper bound: a(n) <= (2^n)!.
%C A046873 Number of linear extensions of the Boolean lattice 2^n. - _Mitch Harris_, Dec 27 2005
%C A046873 The number of vertices in the representation of all linear extensions in a distributive lattice are the Dedekind numbers (A000372) and the number of edges constitutes A118077. - _Oliver Wienand_, Apr 11 2006
%C A046873 A lower bound is A051459(n) = Product_{k=0..n} binomial(n,k)! <= a(n). - _Geoffrey Critzer_, May 20 2018
%H A046873 J. Daniel Christensen, <a href="/A046873/b046873.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..7</a>
%H A046873 Gleb Beliakov and Chaquen Beliakov Amaya, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.fss.2026.109989">Algorithms for random generation fuzzy measures with empirical validation of the uniformity of sample distributions</a>, Fuzzy Sets and Systems 542 (2026), Art. 109989.
%H A046873 Andrew Beveridge, Ian Calaway, and Kristin Heysse, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1912.12319">de Finetti Lattices and Magog Triangles</a>, arXiv:1912.12319 [math.CO], 2019.
%H A046873 Graham R. Brightwell, and Prasad Tetali, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1023/B:ORDE.0000034596.50352.f7">The number of linear extensions of the Boolean lattice</a>, Order 20(4) (2003), 333-345. (Gives asymptotics.)
%H A046873 Andries E. Brouwer and J. Daniel Christensen, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1702.03018">Counterexamples to conjectures about Subset Takeaway and counting linear extensions of a Boolean lattice</a>, arXiv:1702.03018 [math.CO], 2017. (Gives n=7 result.)
%H A046873 Ji Chang Sha and D. J. Kleitman, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/0012-365X(87)90016-1">The number of linear extensions of subset ordering</a>, Discrete Math. 63(2-3) (1987), 271-278.
%H A046873 Jian-Zhang Wu and Gleb Beliakov, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2309.15399">Generating fuzzy measures from additive measures</a>, arXiv:2309.15399 [math.GM], 2023. See p. 8.
%e A046873 a(2)=2 because either {}<{0}<{1}<{0,1} or {}<{1}<{0}<{0,1}.
%Y A046873 Cf. A001206, A114717, A000372, A118077.
%K A046873 nonn,nice
%O A046873 0,3
%A A046873 _David A. Madore_
%E A046873 a(5) from _Oliver Wienand_, Apr 11 2006, using Python and an inference method for computing the set of linear extensions of arbitrary posets. Using the same method on a compute server generated a(6) on Dec 05 2010.
%E A046873 a(7) from _J. Daniel Christensen_, Feb 13 2017, based on Brouwer-Christensen work cited above, using C.
